body: Hi thanks for trying our C# support. If I remember correctly we have discussed this item before in the meeting @jignparm would you mind following up this issue?

The framework side of this is being tracked by https://github.com/dotnet/corefx/issues/25702 and is being prototyped under https://github.com/dotnet/corefxlab/issues/2635.

There are also discussions to ensure that it gets the appropriate language support in C# (and potentially other languages like F#).
ORT will also need to expose the support via C# API, @faxu for tracking it.

The ORT C#  API maps several tensor native types to C# system types (e.g. Int64 -> long, see below). Currently Bloat16 is not implemented. Ideal solution is to have  Bfloat16 implemented as a new type in C# as @tannergooding mentioned above.

https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime/blob/master/csharp/src/Microsoft.ML.OnnxRuntime/NamedOnnxValue.cs#L327

@jignparm, do you need both `bfloat16` (Google's format) and `float16` (the IEEE half-precision format)? 

We have proposals to support both currently and will likely end up implementing both, but I just want to make sure I have it tracked correctly.

I observed a similar problem when using the Python API after converting my model to float16 (using the ONNX [converter script](https://github.com/onnx/onnx-docker/blob/master/onnx-ecosystem/converter_scripts/float32_float16_onnx.ipynb)):
> RuntimeError: **Numpy_type 23 can't be converted to MLDataType**.

Is this related to the C# fix or should I open a new issue?

Tested with the CPU version of the onnxruntime 0.4.0 using `pip install onnxruntime`.

> Is there a timeline for the proposal? 

I believe the current target is .NET 5, but it also depends largely on prioritization and scheduling.

issue.title: FP16 in .NET 5
issue.body: According to [this github issue](https://github.com/Microsoft/onnxruntime/issues/948) native FP16 support is most likely going to land in .NET 5, so reimplementing the benchmark then would probably be a good idea. This is a tracking issue for that.

issue.title: Feature: Backend.None typed tensors
issue.body:
(Replaces #73, using a feature branch)

The plan is that DiffSharp 1.0 will support the usual PyTorch range of typed tensors.
This implements typed tensors for `DiffSharp.Backend.None`. 

There is no real hurry to merge this, I can maintain it as `dev` progresses.

Backend.None types share code in `RawTensorCPU<T>`. The non-math code for raw CPU tensors moves to `RawTensorCPU`. The math code for is in a module `RawTensorCPU` using generic inline code. Specific types inherit and incorporate the code needed for construction

For Int32, operations like "t.Sin()" on Int32 tensors first convert to a Float32 tensor and implicitly return a Float32 tensor, though we could make them just fail.

Testing is expanded out to test the full range of types.

Pros:

1. Complete the matrix for Backend.None
2. Bug-for-bug consistency across the CPU tensor types
3. The interactions betwewen the CPU tensor types can be dealt with in one place consistently
4. Performance should be no worse than before since the math code is inlined.
5. Perf improvements apply across all RawTensorCPU types

Cons:

1. Adding an operation requires writing a line of code for each of RawTensorFloat32CPU, RawTensorFloat64CPU, RawTensorInt32CPU. You can prototype only with Float32 and do the generalize later.

2. Writing the generic inline math code can be tricky, though I've done my best to make it simple.

body: This issue has been automatically marked as stale due to inactivity and will be closed in 7 days if no further activity occurs. If further support is needed, please provide an update and/or more details.
What is the latest on this?

.NET 5 is shipping `System.Half` as an interchange type: https://devblogs.microsoft.com/dotnet/introducing-the-half-type/

This means you can parse/format strings, do basic comparison/equality checks, and convert to/from `float` and `double`. Other operations, such as addition, subtraction, and language literals aren't available.

If language support is needed, I'd recommend opening an issue on dotnet/csharplang requesting it and detailing the requirements, reasons, and scenarios.
